Tatsuyama Stone has been transported via the {{ill|Hokkesan Tanigawa River|ja|法華山谷川|12=draft}} (Araikawa River) to various parts of western Japan. It has been widely used in construction, including ancient structures such as the {{ill|stone coffin|ja|石棺|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Daisenryō Kofun|ja|大仙陵古墳|1=Daisenryō Kofun|12=draft}} (burial site of Emperor Nintoku), long box-shaped stone coffins, and house-shaped stone coffins from the mid-Kofun period. Other uses include foundation stones of the {{ill|Heijō Palace|ja|平城宮|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kuni-kyō|ja|恭仁宮|gg=Kuni-kyō|lt=Kuni Palace|12=draft}} during the {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代|12=draft}}, the pedestal of the {{ill|Asuka-dera|ja|飛鳥大仏|11=Asuka-dera|lt=Asuka Great Buddha|12=draft}}, stone walls of {{ill|Himeji Castle|ja|姫路城|12=draft}}, and more modern structures such as the {{ill|Tokyo Imperial Palace|ja|皇居|12=draft}} grounds, the {{ill|National Diet Building|ja|国会議事堂|12=draft}}, and architectural landmarks like the {{ill|Former Coinage Bureau Building|ja|旧造幣寮鋳造所正面玄関|12=draft}}, {{ill|Sumitomo Bank Osaka Head Office Building|ja|三井住友銀行大阪本店ビル|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Nagoya Civic Assembly Hall|ja|名古屋市公会堂|12=draft}}.<ref name="shitei" /> Tatsuyama Stone has also been used for waymarkers, residential walls, gates, tombstones, and monuments, and remains a choice material for cultural property restoration, including the stone walls of Himeji Castle and other notable sites.<ref>[http://www.kobe-np.co.jp/news/shakai/201501/0007703615.shtml Tatsuyama Stone: Reviving a 1,700-Year Quarrying Legacy for Cultural Heritage Restoration] {{ill|Kobe Shimbun|ja|神戸新聞|12=draft}}{{dead link|date=July 2020}}</ref>

