[[File:Tatsuyama stone.jpg|thumb|Ishi no Hōden and Tatsuyama Stone Quarry Ruins]]
'''Tatsuyama Stone Quarry Ruins''' (竜山石採石遺跡, Tatsuyamaishi Saiseki Iseki) are archaeological remains located in {{ill|Takasago, Hyōgo|ja|高砂市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|ja|兵庫県|12=draft}}, Japan. Together with the nearby {{ill|lt=Ishi no Hōden|Ishi no Hōden#Aokigami Shrine's Ishi no Hōden|ja|石の宝殿|12=draft}}, situated about 200 meters away, the site has been designated as a {{ill|Historic Site (Japan)|ja|史跡|1=Historic site|lt=Historic site of Japan|12=draft}}} by the Japanese government.<ref name="文化遺産オンライン" />

== Overview ==
The Tatsuyama Stone Quarry Ruins span a total area of 670,000 square meters, with traces of quarrying observed across 162 locations. These sites document the production of {{ill|Tatsuyama Stone|ja|竜山石|12=draft}}, a type of stone material quarried in Takasago City for approximately 1,700 years, from the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft}} to the present day.<ref name="shitei">[http://www.hyogo-c.ed.jp/~board-bo/kisya26/2606/2606195.pdf Regarding the Designation of Historic Sites, Scenic Spots, and Natural Monuments (National Historic Sites)] Hyōgo Prefecture Board of Education {{dead link|date=July 2020}}</ref> On {{ill|October 6, 2014|ja|2014th year 10月6日|12=draft}}, an 110,000-square-meter section spanning 31 sites across {{ill|Mount Tatsuyama (Hyōgo)|ja|竜山|12=draft}} and {{ill|Mount Hōden|ja|宝殿山|12=draft}} was designated a National Historic Site as part of the "Ishi no Hōden and Tatsuyama Stone Quarry Ruins" group.<ref name="文化遺産オンライン">{{文化遺産オンライン|210377|Ishi no Hōden and Tatsuyama Stone Quarry Ruins}}</ref> This is the first ancient stone quarry to receive such a designation.<ref name="shitei" /><ref>[https://www.sankei.com/article/20140621-DL7M3INHVFINPOAXAFCBCSR2PE/ National Historic Site Designation for Ishi no Hōden and Tatsuyama Stone Quarry Ruins Recommended to the Minister of Education] {{ill|Sankei Shimbun|ja|産経新聞|12=draft}}</ref>

