== Overview ==
The Tatsuyama Stone Quarry Ruins span a total area of 670,000 square meters, with traces of quarrying observed across 162 locations. These sites document the production of {{ill|Tatsuyama Stone|ja|竜山石|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a type of stone material quarried in Takasago City for approximately 1,700 years, from the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to the present day.<ref name="shitei">[http://www.hyogo-c.ed.jp/~board-bo/kisya26/2606/2606195.pdf Regarding the Designation of Historic Sites, Scenic Spots, and Natural Monuments (National Historic Sites)] Hyōgo Prefecture Board of Education {{dead link|date=July 2020}}</ref> On {{ill|October 6, 2014|ja|2014th year 10月6日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, an 110,000-square-meter section spanning 31 sites across {{ill|Mount Tatsuyama (Hyōgo)|ja|竜山|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Mount Hōden|ja|宝殿山|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was designated a National Historic Site as part of the "Ishi no Hōden and Tatsuyama Stone Quarry Ruins" group.<ref name="文化遺産オンライン">{{文化遺産オンライン|210377|Ishi no Hōden and Tatsuyama Stone Quarry Ruins}}</ref> This is the first ancient stone quarry to receive such a designation.<ref name="shitei" /><ref>[https://www.sankei.com/article/20140621-DL7M3INHVFINPOAXAFCBCSR2PE/ National Historic Site Designation for Ishi no Hōden and Tatsuyama Stone Quarry Ruins Recommended to the Minister of Education] {{ill|Sankei Shimbun|ja|産経新聞|qq=draft|qq=draft}}</ref>

=== Tatsuyama Stone ===
Tatsuyama Stone, quarried from the {{ill|Hōden geological layer|ja|宝殿層|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on the right bank of the {{ill|Kako River (Japan)|lt=Kakogawa River|ja|加古川|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, was traditionally classified as a type of tuffaceous rhyolitic welded tuff. Recent studies have identified it as rhyolitic {{ill|hyaloclastite|ja|ハイアロクラスタイト|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, formed approximately 100 million years ago during the late {{ill|Cretaceous|ja|白亜紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Volcanic activity generated magma that erupted into a caldera lake, rapidly cooling and fragmenting upon contact with the water.<ref>[https://www.gsj.jp/data/50KGM/PDF/GSJ_MAP_G050_12071_2003_D.pdf Geology of the Takasago Area: Chapter 12, Resource Geology, Section 2: Quarrying and Crushed Stone] {{ill|Geological Survey of Japan|ja|地質調査総合センター|qq=draft|qq=draft}}</ref> The stone is easy to process due to its softness, while maintaining strength, resilience, and excellent fire resistance. Its original pale green color often changes over time due to oxidation, with shades of blue, yellow, and red also common. It is also referred to as Hōden Stone.

Tatsuyama Stone has been transported via the {{ill|Hokkesan Tanigawa River|ja|法華山谷川|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Araikawa River) to various parts of western Japan. It has been widely used in construction, including ancient structures such as the {{ill|stone coffin|ja|石棺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of the {{ill|Daisenryō Kofun|ja|大仙陵古墳|1=Daisenryō Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (burial site of Emperor Nintoku), long box-shaped stone coffins, and house-shaped stone coffins from the mid-Kofun period. Other uses include foundation stones of the {{ill|Heijō Palace|ja|平城宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Kuni-kyō|ja|恭仁宮|gg=Kuni-kyō|lt=Kuni Palace|qq=draft|qq=draft}} during the {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the pedestal of the {{ill|Asuka-dera|ja|飛鳥大仏|11=Asuka-dera|lt=Asuka Great Buddha|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, stone walls of {{ill|Himeji Castle|ja|姫路城|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and more modern structures such as the {{ill|Tokyo Imperial Palace|ja|皇居|qq=draft|qq=draft}} grounds, the {{ill|National Diet Building|ja|国会議事堂|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and architectural landmarks like the {{ill|Former Coinage Bureau Building|ja|旧造幣寮鋳造所正面玄関|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Sumitomo Bank Osaka Head Office Building|ja|三井住友銀行大阪本店ビル|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Nagoya Civic Assembly Hall|ja|名古屋市公会堂|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="shitei" /> Tatsuyama Stone has also been used for waymarkers, residential walls, gates, tombstones, and monuments, and remains a choice material for cultural property restoration, including the stone walls of Himeji Castle and other notable sites.<ref>[http://www.kobe-np.co.jp/news/shakai/201501/0007703615.shtml Tatsuyama Stone: Reviving a 1,700-Year Quarrying Legacy for Cultural Heritage Restoration] {{ill|Kobe Shimbun|ja|神戸新聞|qq=draft|qq=draft}}{{dead link|date=July 2020}}</ref>

