=== Tatsuyama Stone ===
Tatsuyama Stone, quarried from the {{ill|Hōden geological layer|ja|宝殿層|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōden geological layer|qq=}} on the right bank of the {{ill|Kako River (Japan)|lt=Kakogawa River|ja|加古川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kako River (Japan)|qq=}}, was traditionally classified as a type of tuffaceous rhyolitic welded tuff. Recent studies have identified it as rhyolitic {{ill|hyaloclastite|ja|ハイアロクラスタイト|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/hyaloclastite|qq=}}, formed approximately 100 million years ago during the late {{ill|Cretaceous|ja|白亜紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cretaceous|qq=}}. Volcanic activity generated magma that erupted into a caldera lake, rapidly cooling and fragmenting upon contact with the water.<ref>[https://www.gsj.jp/data/50KGM/PDF/GSJ_MAP_G050_12071_2003_D.pdf Geology of the Takasago Area: Chapter 12, Resource Geology, Section 2: Quarrying and Crushed Stone] {{ill|Geological Survey of Japan|ja|地質調査総合センター|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Geological Survey of Japan|qq=}}</ref> The stone is easy to process due to its softness, while maintaining strength, resilience, and excellent fire resistance. Its original pale green color often changes over time due to oxidation, with shades of blue, yellow, and red also common. It is also referred to as Hōden Stone.

Tatsuyama Stone has been transported via the {{ill|Hokkesan Tanigawa River|ja|法華山谷川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hokkesan Tanigawa River|qq=}} (Araikawa River) to various parts of western Japan. It has been widely used in construction, including ancient structures such as the {{ill|stone coffin|ja|石棺|1=Sekkan|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/stone coffin|13=User:Immanuelle/Sekkan|qq=}} of the {{ill|Daisenryō Kofun|ja|大仙陵古墳|1=Daisenryō Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisenryō Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisenryō Kofun|qq=}} (burial site of Emperor Nintoku), long box-shaped stone coffins, and house-shaped stone coffins from the mid-Kofun period. Other uses include foundation stones of the {{ill|Heijō Palace|ja|平城宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heijō Palace|qq=}} and {{ill|Kuni-kyō|ja|恭仁宮|gg=Kuni-kyō|lt=Kuni Palace|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuni-kyō|qq=}} during the {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara period|qq=}}, the pedestal of the {{ill|Asuka-dera|ja|飛鳥大仏|11=Asuka-dera|lt=Asuka Great Buddha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asuka-dera|qq=}}, stone walls of {{ill|Himeji Castle|ja|姫路城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Himeji Castle|qq=}}, and more modern structures such as the {{ill|Tokyo Imperial Palace|ja|皇居|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyo Imperial Palace|qq=}} grounds, the {{ill|National Diet Building|ja|国会議事堂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Diet Building|qq=}}, and architectural landmarks like the {{ill|Former Coinage Bureau Building|ja|旧造幣寮鋳造所正面玄関|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Former Coinage Bureau Building|qq=}}, {{ill|Sumitomo Bank Osaka Head Office Building|ja|三井住友銀行大阪本店ビル|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumitomo Bank Osaka Head Office Building|qq=}}, and {{ill|Nagoya Civic Assembly Hall|ja|名古屋市公会堂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagoya Civic Assembly Hall|qq=}}.<ref name="shitei" /> Tatsuyama Stone has also been used for waymarkers, residential walls, gates, tombstones, and monuments, and remains a choice material for cultural property restoration, including the stone walls of Himeji Castle and other notable sites.<ref>[http://www.kobe-np.co.jp/news/shakai/201501/0007703615.shtml Tatsuyama Stone: Reviving a 1,700-Year Quarrying Legacy for Cultural Heritage Restoration] {{ill|Kobe Shimbun|ja|神戸新聞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kobe Shimbun|qq=}}{{dead link|date=July 2020}}</ref>

