Tatsuyama Stone has been transported via the {{ill|Hokkesan Tanigawa River|ja|法華山谷川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hokkesan Tanigawa River|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (Araikawa River) to various parts of western Japan. It has been widely used in construction, including ancient structures such as the {{ill|stone coffin|ja|石棺|1=Sekkan|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/stone coffin|13=User:Immanuelle/Sekkan|qq=}} of the {{ill|Daisenryō Kofun|ja|大仙陵古墳|1=Daisenryō Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisenryō Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisenryō Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} (burial site of Emperor Nintoku), long box-type stone coffins, and house-shaped stone coffins from the mid-Kofun period. Other uses include foundation stones of the [[:en:Heijō Palace|Heijō Palace]] and {{ill|Kuni-kyō|ja|恭仁宮|gg=Kuni-kyō|lt=Kuni Palace|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuni-kyō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 恭仁京}} during the [[:en:Nara period|Nara period]], the pedestal of the {{ill|Asuka-dera|ja|飛鳥大仏|11=Asuka-dera|lt=Asuka Great Buddha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asuka-dera|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 飛鳥寺}}, stone walls of [[:en:Himeji Castle|Himeji Castle]], and more modern structures such as the [[:en:Tokyo Imperial Palace|Tokyo Imperial Palace]] grounds, the [[:en:National Diet Building|National Diet Building]], and architectural landmarks like the {{ill|Former Coinage Bureau Building|ja|旧造幣寮鋳造所正面玄関|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Former Coinage Bureau Building|qq=}}, {{ill|Sumitomo Bank Osaka Head Office Building|ja|三井住友銀行大阪本店ビル|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumitomo Bank Osaka Head Office Building|qq=}}, and [[:en:Nagoya Civic Assembly Hall|Nagoya Civic Assembly Hall]].<ref name="shitei" /> Tatsuyama Stone has also been used for waymarkers, residential walls, gates, tombstones, and monuments, and remains a choice material for cultural property restoration, including the stone walls of Himeji Castle and other notable sites.<ref>[http://www.kobe-np.co.jp/news/shakai/201501/0007703615.shtml Tatsuyama Stone: Reviving a 1,700-Year Quarrying Legacy for Cultural Heritage Restoration] [[:en:Kobe Shimbun|Kobe Shimbun]]{{dead link|date=July 2020}}</ref>
